The paper discusses deep learning models and their computational constraints, which are typically addressed through model compression techniques. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) or Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper specifically mentions convolutional layers, which are commonly used in computer vision tasks, indicating that the paper could also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also introduces a novel training scheme, which could fall under the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the paper addresses the challenge of supporting deep learning services with dynamic workload cost-effectively, which could be relevant to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category.
